refined_goal: Build a privacy-preserving, API-free geolocation engine that determines a device‚Äôs coarse-to-fine physical location by fusing multi-layer network signals, without calling third‚Äëparty geolocation APIs. The system leverages: Playwright to instrument browser-grade timing and WebRTC ICE candidates; Uptime-Kuma as a resilient scheduler/telemetry store; Sniffnet for passive packet capture and RTT fingerprinting; Hoppscotch to craft protocol probes; yt-dlp to trigger CDN edge selection with region-coded hosts; frp for optional reverse-path anchoring; React/Dioxus for UX; and javascript-algorithms for robust multilateration/optimization. Success criteria: median error ‚â§ 25‚Äì50 km in urban regions and ‚â§ 150‚Äì250 km in rural, 95th percentile fix under 20 s, zero dependence on commercial geolocation APIs, and reproducibility across ISPs/NATs. Why it matters: shifts location inference from data brokerage to locally auditable network physics‚Äîtransparent, portable, and private by design.
repository_synergy:
THE INSIGHT: These repos weren‚Äôt built for geolocation‚Äîbut together they can make the network itself the map. Uptime-Kuma excels at resilient scheduling and time-series metrics; Sniffnet reads the wire with precision; Playwright produces browser-grade timing, TLS/HTTP/2/3 metrics, and WebRTC ICE candidates; Hoppscotch composes multi-protocol requests; yt-dlp coerces CDNs into showing their closest edge; frp flips NAT traversal to enable reverse probing; React/Dioxus provide the UX; javascript-algorithms supplies the math glue. No one of these solves geolocation; as a set, they let us infer location from how the Internet routes to you‚Äîno API required.

THE STORY: Instead of asking a geolocation API ‚ÄúWhere am I?‚Äù, we make distributed networks answer implicitly. CDNs and anycast DNS always steer you to a nearby PoP. If we time the handshakes (TCP/TLS/QUIC), parse PoP identifiers in headers/hostnames, and observe RTT patterns, we can triangulate location. Uptime-Kuma, designed for uptime checks, becomes a high-volume, accurate measurement orchestrator. Sniffnet‚Äôs Rust packet engine provides precise timestamps and protocol-level observability for noise reduction. Playwright‚Äôs headless Chromium yields consistent client-side timings, and exposes STUN-derived ICE candidates to differentiate private/public IP contexts. Hoppscotch gives us a programmable bench to craft HTTP/WebSocket/GraphQL/SSH probes that bypass CORS and exercise different network paths. yt-dlp forces connections to YouTube/Google video edge nodes whose hostnames and response traits leak PoP vicinity. frp sets up an optional reverse tunnel so a remote anchor can ping and traceroute to you even behind CGNAT, disambiguating misleading outbound-only latencies.

THE SYNERGY: The unexpected bridge is using Uptime-Kuma not as a mere monitor but as the distributed probe scheduler and store; it normalizes multi-target latency/availability checks and exposes history for statistical calibration. Sniffnet filters the exact flows Kuma or Playwright initiate, providing precise RTT distributions and handshake decomposition that browsers obscure. Playwright both gathers browser metrics and runs the STUN ICE trick‚Äîwithout a geolocation permission dialog. Hoppscotch turbocharges iteration on PoP inventories and headers to extract region codes. javascript-algorithms implements weighted least squares and robust estimators to convert latency surfaces into coordinates, with uncertainty bands. React/Dioxus then turn abstract signal stacks into transparent, explainable location inferences. 

THE INNOVATION: We‚Äôre not scraping a location service; we‚Äôre measuring Internet physics and CDN economics. By composing these repos, we get a portable, auditable geolocation fabric that improves with a richer PoP catalog and better timing‚Äîbut never needs an external geolocation API. It‚Äôs vendor-neutral, privacy-first, and works in constrained environments. The aha moment: Uptime-Kuma‚Äôs monitors + Sniffnet‚Äôs packet timestamps + Playwright‚Äôs browser reality create a repeatable lab that turns proxy/NAT ambiguity into solvable geometry.
technical_architecture:
Components and flows:
- Probe Orchestrator (Uptime-Kuma): Define custom monitors as ‚Äúgeo-monitors‚Äù. Each monitor targets a curated set of anycast/CDN endpoints (e.g., Cloudflare probe paths, Google/YouTube static assets, Fastly test objects), running ICMP, TCP SYN, TLS handshake, and HTTP GET checks at staggered intervals. Store results in Kuma‚Äôs SQLite with timestamps, status, and per-stage latencies.
- Passive Capture (Sniffnet): Run a companion Rust agent with BPF filters matching probe flows (by dst IP/port list). Capture kernel-level timestamps for SYN/SYN-ACK, TLS ClientHello/ServerHello, and first-HTTP-byte. Produce per-flow records: RTT, jitter, packet loss, and initial TTL clues. This denoises Kuma‚Äôs app-level times and detects middleboxes.
- Browser-grade Tracing (Playwright): Headless Chromium scripts execute: (1) WebRTC ICE gathering to reveal reflexive candidates (public IP/port) and host candidates (LAN hints) without requesting geolocation; (2) Navigation to the same CDN endpoints to collect NavigationTiming, ResourceTiming, HTTP/2 push/HTTP/3 alt-svc, and server headers that sometimes embed PoP codes; (3) Cross-origin request exercises that real sites trigger (e.g., H/2 priorities) to mimic realistic paths.
- Protocol Composer (Hoppscotch): Embedded developer console to craft and iterate probe requests (HTTP/WS/GraphQL), batch them, and export into Kuma monitor definitions. Operators can test new PoP endpoints live and promote to scheduled probes.
- CDN Edge Revelation (yt-dlp): Trigger video segment fetches to force edge selection; parse verbose logs for server IPs, hostnames, and response headers that often carry edge identifiers. Feed hostnames/IPs back into the PoP resolver.
- Optional Reverse Anchor (frp): Client establishes a reverse tunnel to a controlled cloud node. The anchor then pings/traceroutes into the client through the tunnel, measuring reverse-path and asymmetry. This resolves cases where outbound anycast hides true geography due to proxies/VPNs.
- Inference Engine (javascript-algorithms + custom): Run weighted least squares on PoP distances inferred from RTTs: minimize Œ£ w_i (|x - p_i| ‚àí Œ±*RTT_i ‚àí Œ≤)^2, where p_i are PoP coordinates, Œ±,Œ≤ are calibration parameters learned from baseline controls (median of known local loops), w_i reflect signal quality (low jitter, consistent headers). Produce a coordinate with confidence ellipse and an explanation graph.
- UI (React/Dioxus): Web UI in React; native shell in Dioxus for offline and kiosk deployments. Views: live signals, PoP hits map, error cones, route asymmetry, ICE candidates, and a trust report (no third-party geolocation API used). 
- Plugin Bus (MCP servers): Expose the probe/inference functions as MCP tools so external controllers can orchestrate experiments programmatically, whether or not an LLM is attached.

Key challenges and solutions:
- Noise and asymmetry: Combine active (Kuma/Playwright) with passive (Sniffnet) to separate app overhead from wire latency; estimate per-endpoint Œ±,Œ≤ via rolling calibration; use median-of-medians and Huber loss for robustness.
- CORS and cross-protocol access: Playwright runs headless to bypass browser restrictions; Hoppscotch targets server-side proxies when needed within the same host network.
- NAT/VPN confounders: ICE candidates reveal public vs. private; frp reverse probing distinguishes actual last-mile from exit-node paths.
- Performance: Concurrency-limited probe batches; reuse Playwright browser contexts; Sniffnet zero-copy capture; histogram aggregation; prune low-value endpoints.
- Interfaces: Kuma‚Äôs API for monitor CRUD; Sniffnet agent over a local gRPC/IPC; Playwright scripts as Node workers; results normalized into a common schema for the inference engine.
expected_impact:
Use cases:
1) Enterprise data residency audits: Verify that employee traffic in Paris resolves to EU PoPs, not US, by scheduled probes and reverse-path checks, with explainable evidence.
2) Consumer VPN transparency: Show where your effective network presence is, not where the VPN claims‚Äîusing ICE candidates, PoP hits, and route asymmetry.
3) CDN placement validation: ISPs/CDNs evaluate whether customers are consistently served from intended edges; anomalies flag misconfigurations or peering shifts.
4) Compliance in regulated sectors: Hospitals or banks prove data locality without exposing PII or calling external geolocation APIs‚Äîlocal-only processing with auditable logs.
5) Offline or constrained ops: Field teams run the Dioxus app without Internet beyond a handful of public anycast endpoints; still infer approximate location from minimal probes.
6) Web perf observability: Correlate TTFB improvements with edge proximity; identify when H/3 handshakes come from unexpected regions.
7) Incident triage: During outages, quickly determine if traffic got re-routed to distant PoPs, explaining sudden latency spikes.

Scalability and extensibility: Uptime-Kuma scales monitors across fleets; probes are stateless and parallelizable; PoP catalogs can be updated incrementally. Adding new CDNs or anycast DNS providers is a data exercise, not a code rewrite. Limitations: Rural areas and high-latency links widen error bounds; CGNAT/proxying can mask reality; some CDNs obfuscate PoP IDs. Mitigations: increase endpoint diversity, use frp reverse anchors, emphasize confidence intervals, and favor passive timing with Sniffnet over application clocks.
innovation_analysis:
Innovation score: 8.7/10. It reframes geolocation as a composable measurement problem using well-maintained, widely adopted repos in novel roles: Uptime-Kuma as a probe orchestrator, Sniffnet as a precision-timing sidecar, Playwright/yt-dlp as CDN-revelation tools, and Hoppscotch for rapid PoP test development‚Äîno traditional geolocation APIs.

Next steps:
- Curate an initial PoP endpoint catalog (Cloudflare, Google/YouTube, Fastly) with coordinates and parsing rules.
- Implement the Sniffnet sidecar filters and gRPC schema; integrate with Kuma result ingestion.
- Build Playwright scripts for ICE collection and timing capture; wire into the orchestrator.
- Implement the weighted least squares solver with calibration and uncertainty estimation.
- Ship a minimal React UI showing signals, estimate, and confidence.

Key metrics: median/95th percentile error (km), time-to-fix (s), probe overhead (kB), reproducibility across runs/ISPs, and share of estimates with high confidence. Essential tools: Uptime-Kuma, Sniffnet (with libpcap), Playwright, Hoppscotch, yt-dlp, frp (optional), React/Dioxus, and javascript-algorithms for the solver.

sources.name: modelcontextprotocol/servers
sources.readme_snippet:
# Model Context Protocol servers

This repository is a collection of *reference implementations* for the [Model Context Protocol](https://modelcontextprotocol.io/) (MCP), as well as references to community-built servers and additional resources.

The servers in this repository showcase the versatility and extensibility of MCP, demonstrating how it can be used to give Large Language Models (LLMs) secure, controlled access to tools and data sources.
Typically, each MCP server is implemented with an MCP SDK:

- [C# MCP SDK](https://github.com/modelcontextprotocol/csharp-sdk)
- [Go MCP SDK](https://github.com/modelcontextprotocol/go-sdk)
- [Java MCP SDK](https://github.com/modelcontextprotocol/java-sdk)
- [Kotlin MCP SDK](https://github.com/modelcontextprotocol/kotlin-sdk)
- [PHP MCP SDK](https://github.com/modelcontextprotocol/php-sdk)
- [Python MCP SDK](https://github.com/modelcontextprotocol/python-sdk)
- [Ruby MCP SDK](https://github.com/modelcontextprotocol/ruby-sdk)
- [Rust MCP SDK](https://github.com/modelcontextprotocol/rust-sdk)
- [Swift MCP SDK](https://github.com/modelcontextprotocol/swift-sdk)
- [TypeScript MCP SDK](https://github.com/modelcontextprotocol/typescript-sdk)

> [!NOTE]
> Lists in this README are maintained in alphabetical order to minimize merge conflicts when adding new items.

## üåü Reference Servers

These servers aim to demonstrate MCP features and the official SDKs.

- **[Everything](src/everything)** - Reference / test server with prompts, resources, and tools.
- **[Fetch](src/fetch)** - Web content fetching and conversion for efficient LLM usage.
- **[Filesystem](src/filesystem)** - Secure file operations with configurable access controls.
- **[Git](src/git)** - Tools to read, search, and manipulate Git repositories.
- **[Memory](src/memory)** - Knowledge graph-based persistent memory system.
- **[Sequential Thinking](src/sequentialthinking)** - Dynamic and reflective problem-solving through thought sequences.
- **[Time](src/time)** - Time

# [React](https://react.dev/) · [![GitHub license](https://img.shields.io/badge/license-MIT-blue.svg)](https://github.com/facebook/react/blob/main/LICENSE) [![npm version](https://img.shields.io/npm/v/react.svg?style=flat)](https://www.npmjs.com/package/react) [![(Runtime) Build and Test](https://github.com/facebook/react/actions/workflows/runtime_build_and_test.yml/badge.svg)](https://github.com/facebook/react/actions/workflows/runtime_build_and_test.yml) [![(Compiler) TypeScript](https://github.com/facebook/react/actions/workflows/compiler_typescript.yml/badge.svg?branch=main)](https://github.com/facebook/react/actions/workflows/compiler_typescript.yml) [![PRs Welcome](https://img.shields.io/badge/PRs-welcome-brightgreen.svg)](https://legacy.reactjs.org/docs/how-to-contribute.html#your-first-pull-request)

React is a JavaScript library for building user interfaces.

* **Declarative:** React makes it painless to create interactive UIs. Design simple views for each state in your application, and React will efficiently update and render just the right components when your data changes. Declarative views make your code more predictable, simpler to understand, and easier to debug.
* **Component-Based:** Build encapsulated components that manage their own state, then compose them to make complex UIs. Since component logic is written in JavaScript instead of templates, you can easily pass rich data through your app and keep the state out of the DOM.
* **Learn Once, Write Anywhere:** We don't make assumptions about the rest of your technology stack, so you can develop new features in React without rewriting existing code. React can also render on the server using [Node](https://nodejs.org/en) and power mobile apps using [React Native](https://reactnative.dev/).

[Learn how to use React in your project](https://react.dev/learn).

sources.name: YaLTeR/niri
sources.readme_snippet:
A scrollable-tiling Wayland compositor.

Getting Started | Configuration | Setup Showcase

![niri with a few windows open](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/535e6530-2f44-4b84-a883-1240a3eee6e9) ## About Windows are arranged in columns on an infinite strip going to the right. Opening a new window never causes existing windows to resize. Every monitor has its own separate window strip. Windows can never "overflow" onto an adjacent monitor. Workspaces are dynamic and arranged vertically. Every monitor has an independent set of workspaces, and there's always one empty workspace present all the way down. The workspace arrangement is preserved across disconnecting and connecting monitors where it makes sense. When a monitor disconnects, its workspaces will move to another monitor, but upon reconnection they will move back to the original monitor. ## Features - Built from the ground up for scrollable tiling - [Dynamic workspaces](https://yalter.github.io/niri/Workspaces.html) like in GNOME - An [Overview](https://github.com/user-attachments/assets/379a5d1f-acdb-4c11-b36c-e85fd91f0995) that zooms out workspaces and w

sources.name: ossu/computer-science
sources.readme_snippet:
Open Source Society University

Path to a free self-taught education in Computer Science!

# Contents - [Summary](#summary) - [Community](#community) - [Curriculum](#curriculum) - [Code of conduct](#code-of-conduct) - [Team](#team) # Summary The OSSU curriculum is a **complete education in computer science** using online materials. It's not merely for career training or professional development. It's for those who want a proper, *well-rounded* grounding in concepts fundamental to all computing disciplines, and for those who have the discipline, will, and (most importantly!) good habits to obtain this education largely on their own, but with support from a worldwide community of fellow learners. It is designed according to the degree requirements of undergraduate computer science majors, minus general education (non-CS) requirements, as it is assumed most of the people following this curriculum are already educated outside the field of CS. The courses themselves are among the very best in the world, often coming from Harvard, Princeton, MIT, etc., but specifically chosen to meet the following criteria. **Courses must**: - Be open for enrollment - Run regularly (ideally in self-paced format, otherwise running multiple times per year) - Be of generally high quality in teaching materials and pedagogical principles - Match the curricular standards of the [CS 2013](CURRICULAR_GUIDELINES.md): Curriculum Guidelines for Undergraduate Degree Progr
